Yes. Redesign the architecture. Not necessarily the whole app.

My read:

Frontend: C or C++ both fine. You have confidence here.

Backend: stop trying to make AI invent the inference layer. Treat model APIs as hostile/fragile/external.

Best architecture:

BeastApp
  BeastGalleryView
  BeastPipelineView
  BeastInspectorView
BeastProjectModel
  artifacts
  generators
  jobs
BeastEngine
  queueJob()
  cancelJob()
  getJobStatus()
BeastBackend
  Wan22Backend
  QwenImageBackend
  Ltx2Backend
  ComfyBackend
  DiffusersBackend

The important split:

BeastEngine = stable Beast world
Backend = unstable model-specific adapter

So your app never "is Wan22." Your app says:

job = BeastJob::wan22(options);
engine.queue(job);

Then only Wan22Backend knows the ugly facts: file names, safetensors, VAE, scheduler, Python, PyTorch, diffusers, Comfy paths.

C++ is probably a good move for app structure, especially since your brain already likes Objective-C style view/model objects.

I would not make the backend deeply object-oriented though. Keep it boring:

class BeastBackend {
public:
    virtual BackendInfo info() = 0;
    virtual ValidationResult validate(const BeastJob& job) = 0;
    virtual JobResult run(const BeastJob& job, BeastJobContext& ctx) = 0;
};

Then each backend is an adapter.

For Wan22 specifically, your failure point is probably not "C vs C++." It is that Wan/Qwen/LTX are moving targets with model-specific pipelines. Wan2.2 has official Diffusers model repos, ComfyUI has separate model placement expectations, Qwen-Image has its own pipeline/edit variants, and LTX-2 has native pipeline tooling plus Diffusers support.  ￼

So Beast should not own inference yet.

Suggested 0.1 path:

1. Beast C++ shell/app
Gallery, artifacts, jobs, CDI, generator UI.

2. Backend bridge first
Call Python/diffusers or Comfy as a subprocess. Stable JSON in/out.

3. Beast model registry
Do not hardcode paths in UI. Have:

models/
  wan22/
    beast-model.json
  qwen-image/
    beast-model.json
  ltx2/
    beast-model.json

4. One golden backend first
Do Wan22 only. No Qwen, no LTX2 until the adapter pattern survives one real model.

5. Later: native backend
After the app works, replace subprocess/Python backend with tighter integration if still worth it.

Lecture title should maybe be:

"Implementation Details Are Architecture"

Core thesis:

Naming is not decoration. File layout is not decoration. Backend boundaries are not decoration. These are the control surfaces that decide whether the system survives contact with reality.

Final recommendation: move to C++ for Beast2 app architecture, but keep the inference layer behind a brutally small adapter interface. Let Python/PyTorch/diffusers/Comfy absorb model chaos until Beast has enough working artifacts to justify native inference.







  


